Title: Fences Official Trailer #1 (2016) Denzel Washington, Viola Davis Drama Movie HD
Comment: Good movie. Lot's of dialogue...not like most modern movies. I understand people have both positive and negative traits and gaining empathy for the terrible life experiences this man had helps you to forgive and love him despite bad behavior. In addition, he was a good provider. But he was NOT a good father or husband and he did not care. He was controlling more than loving. I saw no concern on his part for how others felt or what they wanted. I still have a hard time thinking this sends a good message to women. For her to stay with him when he informed her how it would be ...that he would continue his affair...and then foist his problem on her....not a good role model.  I understand she was financially dependent, that she loved him, and that she wanted to care for the child. But I would not sleep with him, cook for him, clean his house, or even talk to him. He would be INFORMED of my rules. If his choice was to not come home and not be present, then my job would be to control the money and to care for the child. PERIOD. In addition, she should begin socializing with other men as a single woman.

Title: Fences Official Trailer #1 (2016) Denzel Washington, Viola Davis Drama Movie HD
Comment: Denzel Washington is one of my favorite actors. But this movie was definitely not role model cool. If anything, Denzel's portrayal of Troy Maxson was that of a self centered arrogant jerk. And although Viola Davis mentioned that her role in this film elevates women, I am still scratching my head. If it's about income equality, yes, I agree. But Davis' portrayal of a faithful woman in the film despite Troy having an affair outside of the marriage sort of put women in the stone age. It's as if a woman's role is to accept a man's deficiencies when they occur right in your face. And yes, I get that a lot of women cheat on men during marriages too - no one is perfect. But being specific about this movie, it makes black women in general appear to be at the lowest level on the evolution hierarchical human chain.

This movie in the highlights of it truths tells the raw sides of real life that could have easily turn tragic given the turn of events if compared to the way people behave and believed during the 50's era verses the ways of most people today.  The reality of marriages that stand the test of time and life as depicted here when Denzel not only had an affair but got the other woman pregnant AND was man enough to tell his wife about it, rather than hide it deny the innocent baby coming into the world. This movie does indeed tell the raw dynamics of the human experience and if you're a person that believes in God you can clearly see the tones of FAITH present throughout this story. Great Job Denzel Washington # Director

Title: Fences Official Trailer #1 (2016) Denzel Washington, Viola Davis Drama Movie HD
Comment:
I think that we've seen this story so many times. Why are black people so often (it feels like most movies do this) in pain, struggling, barely getting by, beating the odds, surviving on luck, and then finally a happy ending. We know what's going to happen. We know how the story is going to end. There's The Butler, The Great Debaters, The Pursuit of Happiness, The Help, The Color Purple, The Grave Diggers Daughter, Chiraq, and 12 Years a Slave. For the sake of story telling, shouldn't we have more movies that show black people in different roles? Shouldn't black folks be entitled to have a good time? I bet they're going to nominate this movie for an Academy Award, because these types of movies are the only ones that will get nominated. 
I'm not a Madea fan, but Tyler Perry is very successful despite his bad ratings from critics. He realizes that black people (and all people) want to laugh and have a good time. I don't see his success as a coincidence; he recognized a want that has been so largely ignored by Hollywood.

But I gotta admit, I'm looking forward to and rooting for Fences the most. A small, but powerful story with great actors. I'd love for this to be so good, it wins an Oscar for best picture, best director, best actor and best actress. 

AndÂ for all the circus Will Smith and co. made last year about black filmmakers not being nominated, I didn't want Smith or Spike Lee or the NWA guysÂ to be nominated last year, because they didn't deserve it IMO. But if this is as good as the trailer suggests, I'm rooting for Denzel and co. to win. So really,Â the color of skin has nothing to do with anything and these jilted celebrities should stop making stupid excuses when they don't make a movie that warrants a nomination.

Title: Fences Official Trailer #1 (2016) Denzel Washington, Viola Davis Drama Movie HD
Comment:
This is a sad sad example of a father.

Being a father is more that just providing food, clothing, and shelter.
Yes, a father is supposed to love and like his children.
What father wouldn't?

A child has to learn emotional and social development not only from the mother but also from the father as well.

And if he can't provide that then he needs to step out of the picture.

A child is more than just a body to feed and clothe.

A child, girls and boys have feelings and emotions.

Part of some of the ills of out society is precisely because the father
was not there to provide for the critical emotional support that children need.

A child brought up in an environment where he is not felt loved and supported could turn out to be a criminal or a monster.

I have never seen a child raised up without a supportive father that did not have some kind of serious defect in their personality.

Title: Fences Official Trailer #1 (2016) Denzel Washington, Viola Davis Drama Movie HD
Comment:
I'll be honest and admit that I'm tired of seeing all films with black actors only being about racism, but this seems absolutely GREAT. Seems like we'll get masterclass performances from Denzel and Viola Davis - and the script seems great. 
And on the topic of not wanting to see more movies on racism, I'm only saying so 'cause I just wanna se more black people get roles like John Boyega's in Star Wars where his race doesn't matter at all for the character. It seems like blockbuster movies are getting my idea, but so many indie movies and Oscar contenders only have black actors when the character requires someone of that race. Feeling a bit tired of it at this point.
